#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:5
msgid "DjangoItem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:7
msgid ""
":class:`DjangoItem` is a class of item that gets its fields definition from "
"a Django model, you simply create a :class:`DjangoItem` and specify what "
"Django model it relates to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:11
msgid ""
"Besides of getting the model fields defined on your item, :class:"
"`DjangoItem` provides a method to create and populate a Django model "
"instance with the item data."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:16
msgid "Using DjangoItem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:18
msgid ""
":class:`DjangoItem` works much like ModelForms in Django, you create a "
"subclass and define its ``django_model`` attribute to be a valid Django "
"model. With this you will get an item with a field for each Django model "
"field."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:22
msgid ""
"In addition, you can define fields that aren't present in the model and even "
"override fields that are present in the model defining them in the item."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:25
msgid "Let's see some examples:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:27
msgid "Creating a Django model for the examples::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:29
msgid ""
"from django.db import models\n"
"\n"
"class Person(models.Model):\n"
"    name = models.CharField(max_length=255)\n"
"    age = models.IntegerField()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:35
msgid "Defining a basic :class:`DjangoItem`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:37
msgid ""
"from scrapy.contrib.djangoitem import DjangoItem\n"
"\n"
"class PersonItem(DjangoItem):\n"
"    django_model = Person"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:42
msgid ":class:`DjangoItem` work just like :class:`~scrapy.item.Item`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:44
msgid ""
">>> p = PersonItem()\n"
">>> p['name'] = 'John'\n"
">>> p['age'] = '22'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:48
msgid ""
"To obtain the Django model from the item, we call the extra method :meth:"
"`~DjangoItem.save` of the :class:`DjangoItem`::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:51
msgid ""
">>> person = p.save()\n"
">>> person.name\n"
"'John'\n"
">>> person.age\n"
"'22'\n"
">>> person.id\n"
"1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:59
msgid ""
"The model is already saved when we call :meth:`~DjangoItem.save`, we can "
"prevent this by calling it with ``commit=False``. We can use "
"``commit=False`` in :meth:`~DjangoItem.save` method to obtain an unsaved "
"model::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:63
msgid ""
">>> person = p.save(commit=False)\n"
">>> person.name\n"
"'John'\n"
">>> person.age\n"
"'22'\n"
">>> person.id\n"
"None"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:71
msgid "As said before, we can add other fields to the item::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:73
msgid ""
"import scrapy\n"
"from scrapy.contrib.djangoitem import DjangoItem\n"
"\n"
"class PersonItem(DjangoItem):\n"
"    django_model = Person\n"
"    sex = scrapy.Field()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:82
msgid ""
">>> p = PersonItem()\n"
">>> p['name'] = 'John'\n"
">>> p['age'] = '22'\n"
">>> p['sex'] = 'M'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:87
msgid ""
"fields added to the item won't be taken into account when doing a :meth:"
"`~DjangoItem.save`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:89
msgid "And we can override the fields of the model with your own::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:91
msgid ""
"class PersonItem(DjangoItem):\n"
"    django_model = Person\n"
"    name = scrapy.Field(default='No Name')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:95
msgid ""
"This is useful to provide properties to the field, like a default or any "
"other property that your project uses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:99
msgid "DjangoItem caveats"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:101
msgid ""
"DjangoItem is a rather convenient way to integrate Scrapy projects with "
"Django models, but bear in mind that Django ORM may not scale well if you "
"scrape a lot of items (ie. millions) with Scrapy. This is because a "
"relational backend is often not a good choice for a write intensive "
"application (such as a web crawler), specially if the database is highly "
"normalized and with many indices."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:108
msgid "Django settings set up"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:110
msgid ""
"To use the Django models outside the Django application you need to set up "
"the ``DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE`` environment variable and --in most cases-- "
"modify the ``PYTHONPATH`` environment variable to be able to import the "
"settings module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:115
msgid ""
"There are many ways to do this depending on your use case and preferences. "
"Below is detailed one of the simplest ways to do it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:118
msgid ""
"Suppose your Django project is named ``mysite``, is located in the path ``/"
"home/projects/mysite`` and you have created an app ``myapp`` with the model "
"``Person``. That means your directory structure is something like this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:122
msgid ""
"/home/projects/mysite\n"
"├── manage.py\n"
"├── myapp\n"
"│   ├── __init__.py\n"
"│   ├── models.py\n"
"│   ├── tests.py\n"
"│   └── views.py\n"
"└── mysite\n"
"    ├── __init__.py\n"
"    ├── settings.py\n"
"    ├── urls.py\n"
"    └── wsgi.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:135
msgid ""
"Then you need to add ``/home/projects/mysite`` to the ``PYTHONPATH`` "
"environment variable and set up the environment variable "
"``DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE`` to ``mysite.settings``. That can be done in your "
"Scrapy's settings file by adding the lines below::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:140
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"sys.path.append('/home/projects/mysite')\n"
"\n"
"import os\n"
"os.environ['DJANGO_SETTINGS_MODULE'] = 'mysite.settings'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../topics/djangoitem.rst:146
msgid ""
"Notice that we modify the ``sys.path`` variable instead the ``PYTHONPATH`` "
"environment variable as we are already within the python runtime. If "
"everything is right, you should be able to start the ``scrapy shell`` "
"command and import the model ``Person`` (i.e. ``from myapp.models import "
"Person``)."
msgstr ""
